# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# hyperfine is the **command-line benchmarking tool** from
# sharkdp (the bat / fd / vivid author).  Runs commands
# multiple times, measures statistics, supports parameter
# sweeps + comparisons.  Pivots from blockchain/games
# (R254-R258) into the **performance-measurement tooling
# cluster**.  Sister to bat / fd / hexyl / vivid (in
# corpus).
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine uses **clap's
# BUILDER API** (NOT derive!) — every flag is constructed
# with `Arg::new("name").long("...").short('x').action(...)`
# chained method calls.  This is the **corpus's first
# documented clap v4 builder-API CLI** (every prior round
# R247-R258 used the derive API).  Major pattern milestone.
# Differences vs derive: (a) no struct/enum definitions,
# (b) imperative chained-method construction, (c) attributes
# become method calls (`.action(ArgAction::Set)` ≈
# `#[arg(action = ArgAction::Set)]`), (d) flag names defined
# inline by `.long("foo").short('f')`.  Used when CLI has
# complex builder logic or generated args (less common in
# modern Rust CLIs but still in production at sharkdp).
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine uses **`ArgAction`
# enum** to specify flag behavior — corpus's first
# documented `ArgAction` usage:
#   `ArgAction::Append`  — Vec<String> (repeatable; values
#                          accumulate)
#   `ArgAction::Set`     — single value, last-wins
#   `ArgAction::SetTrue` — bool flag (no value)
# Equivalent derive form: derive auto-detects from the
# field type (Vec<T> → Append, T → Set, bool → SetTrue).
# Builder form requires explicit `.action(...)`.
# Documents the **ArgAction enum** pattern — clap v4's
# unified flag-behavior model (clap v3 used separate
# `Arg::multiple` / `Arg::takes_value` flags).
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine uses
# **`ValueHint::CommandString`** + **`ValueHint::FilePath`**
# — `.value_hint(ValueHint::CommandString)` tells clap
# the value should be auto-completed as a shell command
# string; `.value_hint(ValueHint::FilePath)` as a file
# path.  Documents **clap's ValueHint enum** for shell-
# completion generators (clap_complete reads value_hint
# to emit appropriate shell completions).  Corpus's
# first documented ValueHint usage.  Other ValueHint
# variants: AnyPath, DirPath, ExecutablePath, Username,
# Hostname, Url, EmailAddress, etc.  Important for
# clap_complete-generated completions but the source
# completion itself (this file) implements the hint
# manually via `_files` and `_command_names`.
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine's `--ignore-failure`/`-i`
# uses **`num_args(0..=1) + default_missing_value("all-non-zero")
# + require_equals(true)`** at cli.rs:226-238 — a 3-way
# parameter behavior:
#   `-i`                          → uses default_missing_value
#                                    "all-non-zero"
#   `-i=all-non-zero`             → explicit value
#   `-i=1,2,3`                    → comma-separated exit codes
#   `-i 1,2,3`                    → REJECTED (require_equals)
# Documents the **optional-value flag pattern**:
#   `.num_args(0..=1)` — accepts 0 or 1 values
#   `.default_missing_value("X")` — value when flag given
#                                   bare
#   `.require_equals(true)` — value must be attached with
#                             `=` (not space-separated)
# Corpus's first documented `default_missing_value` +
# `num_args(0..=1)` + `require_equals(true)` triple.
# Useful for "flag with optional value" semantics.
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine's `--parameter-scan`/`-P`
# takes **THREE value names** `["VAR", "MIN", "MAX"]` at
# cli.rs:160 — `.value_names([...])` declares a multi-value
# flag where each value has a distinct display name.  Used
# as `hyperfine -P threads 1 8 'make -j {threads}'`.
# Documents the **multi-value-name flag pattern** — clap
# v4 builder uses `.value_names([...])`; derive uses
# `#[arg(num_args = 3, value_names = ["VAR", "MIN", "MAX"])]`.
# Distinct from R254 subxt's positional FileOrUrl (which
# parses a single string as path-or-URL via FromStr).
# Corpus's first documented multi-value-name flag.
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine's `-N` flag is an
# **alias for `--shell=none`** at cli.rs:219-225 — but
# implemented as a SEPARATE `Arg::new("no-shell")` with
# `conflicts_with_all(["shell", "debug-mode"])`.  NOT an
# `.alias()` on `--shell`.  When `-N` is set, the code at
# main.rs branches on `matches.get_flag("no-shell")` and
# treats it as `--shell=none`.  Documents the **separate-
# flag-as-alias pattern** when the alias has DIFFERENT
# semantic constraints (here: also conflicts with
# --debug-mode).  Distinct from R250 sozo's
# `#[command(alias = "sn")]` (which is true clap-level
# aliasing).
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine's `--shell` uses
# **`.overrides_with("shell")`** at cli.rs:209 — re-
# specifying `--shell=A --shell=B` makes B win (last-one-
# wins).  Without this, clap errors on duplicate flags.
# Documents the **overrides_with-self pattern** for
# "last-flag-wins" semantics.  Corpus's first documented
# `overrides_with` attribute.  Distinct from
# `conflicts_with` (which forbids both) and `requires`
# (which mandates pairing).
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine has **2 HIDDEN
# flags** via `.hide(true)` at cli.rs:397 + 406:
# `--min-benchmarking-time` and `--debug-mode`.  These
# flags work but don't appear in `--help`.  Documents the
# **hidden-flag pattern** for experimental / internal /
# unstable flags that are functional but not yet
# stabilized for public use.  Source comment at cli.rs:391-392
# explains: "This option is hidden for now, as it is not
# yet clear yet if we want to 'stabilize' this".  Corpus's
# first documented `.hide(true)` attribute.
#
# Critical extraction note: hyperfine uses
# **`.hide_default_value(true)`** at cli.rs:261 on
# `--sort` — the default IS `"auto"` (shown via
# `default_value("auto")`) but the `(default: auto)` text
# is HIDDEN in --help to keep the help compact.  Distinct
# from `.hide(true)` (hides the entire flag).  Documents
# **`hide_default_value`** — the default still applies at
# parse time, just isn't shown in help text.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 5 export-format target flags (all take FILE; same shape).
local -a export_flags=(
  '--export-asciidoc=[export timing summary as AsciiDoc table]:file:_files'
  '--export-csv=[export timing summary as CSV (output time unit always seconds)]:file:_files -g "*.csv"'
  '--export-json=[export timing summary + per-run timings as JSON (output time unit always seconds)]:file:_files -g "*.json"'
  '--export-markdown=[export timing summary as Markdown table]:file:_files -g "*.md"'
  '--export-orgmode=[export timing summary as Emacs org-mode table]:file:_files -g "*.org"'
)

_arguments -s -S \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
  '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
  '(-w --warmup)'{-w+,--warmup=}'[perform NUM warmup runs before benchmark (useful for I/O cache filling)]:n:' \
  '(-r --runs -m --min-runs)'{-m+,--min-runs=}'[perform at least NUM runs (default: 10)]:n:' \
  '(-r --runs -M --max-runs)'{-M+,--max-runs=}'[perform at most NUM runs (default: no limit)]:n:' \
  '(-m --min-runs -M --max-runs -r --runs)'{-r+,--runs=}'[perform EXACTLY NUM runs (mutex with min/max-runs)]:n:' \
  '(-s --setup)'{-s+,--setup=}'[execute CMD before each set of timing runs (once per command)]:command:' \
  '--reference=[reference command for relative comparison (default: fastest)]:command:' \
  '--reference-name=[meaningful name for the reference command (REQUIRES --reference)]:name:' \
  '*'{-p+,--prepare=}'[execute CMD before each timing run; repeatable for per-command prepare]:command:' \
  '*'{-C+,--conclude=}'[execute CMD after each timing run; repeatable for per-command conclude]:command:' \
  '(-c --cleanup)'{-c+,--cleanup=}'[execute CMD after all runs complete (for cleanup of artifacts)]:command:' \
  '(-L --parameter-list)'{-P+,--parameter-scan=}'[benchmark range VAR MIN MAX; replaces {VAR} in commands]:VAR:: :MIN:: :MAX::' \
  '(-L --parameter-list)'{-D+,--parameter-step-size=}'[step size DELTA for --parameter-scan (REQUIRES --parameter-scan)]:DELTA:' \
  '*'{-L+,--parameter-list=}'[benchmark per-value in comma-separated list VALUES (mutex with --parameter-scan)]:VAR:: :VALUES::' \
  '(-S --shell)'{-S+,--shell=}'[shell to use for executing commands (name, path, or "default" / "none")]:shell:(default none bash zsh sh fish nushell)' \
  '(-N --no-shell -S --shell --debug-mode)-N[alias for --shell=none (mutex with --shell and --debug-mode)]' \
  '(-i --ignore-failure)'{-i,--ignore-failure}'[ignore failures of benchmarked programs (no value = all-non-zero; or --ignore-failure=1,2)]' \
  '(--show-output)--style=[output style: auto/basic/full/nocolor/color/none]:style:(auto basic full nocolor color none)' \
  '--sort=[sort order: auto (default) / command / mean-time]:method:(auto command mean-time)' \
  '(-u --time-unit)'{-u+,--time-unit=}'[time unit: microsecond / millisecond / second (default: auto)]:unit:(microsecond millisecond second)' \
  $export_flags \
  '(--style --output)--show-output[print stdout/stderr of benchmark commands (slower; for debugging)]' \
  '(--show-output)*--output=[redirect benchmark output: null (default) / pipe / inherit / FILE; repeatable per command]:where:(null pipe inherit)' \
  '--input=[input source: null (default) / FILE]:where:(null)' \
  '*'{-n+,--command-name=}'[meaningful name for a command (repeatable for multiple commands)]:name:' \
  '*:command to benchmark:_command_names'
